194
00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:30.520
So, this is a slide that has been well-worn.

195
00:11:30.550 --> 00:11:32.940
I had it in a review about 10 years ago.

196
00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:36.840
But to be honest with you, the seminal messages from this slide remain.

197
00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:41.310
It is clear that obesity itself, in and of itself, is a risk

198
00:11:41.380 --> 00:11:45.060
factor, of course, not only for cardiovascular disease, but

199
00:11:45.140 --> 00:11:49.100
also it impacts definitely the incidence of

200
00:11:49.660 --> 00:11:53.280
many different cancers, especially cancers of the female

201
00:11:53.340 --> 00:11:56.360
reproductive tract like breast, ovarian, and

202
00:11:56.460 --> 00:12:00.350
particularly endometrial. And in fact, in endometrial cancer, it's thought

203
00:12:00.380 --> 00:12:04.320
that up to 20% of all those cancers can be attributed

204
00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:07.140
back to obesity and the sequelae associated with

205
00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:10.770
obesity.But what is interesting is when you look at this, is

206
00:12:10.830 --> 00:12:14.070
that we have very good basic science that links

207
00:12:14.350 --> 00:12:17.750
obesity through, if you want, the well-fed state, either

208
00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:21.390
triglycerides or sugar, to increases in

209
00:12:21.490 --> 00:12:24.930
production of IGF-1, which is a well-known

210
00:12:25.110 --> 00:12:28.250
promoter of breast cancer growth.

211
00:12:28.830 --> 00:12:32.550
We also know that hyperinsulinemia from dysregulated

212
00:12:33.030 --> 00:12:36.800
glucose metabolism also affects breast cancer, likely by very similar

213
00:12:36.890 --> 00:12:40.070
pathways. And then this is very much of a black box.

214
00:12:40.670 --> 00:12:44.070
Adipose tissue in the wrong place definitely impacts cancer

215
00:12:44.130 --> 00:12:47.990
biology, not only because of the classical responses, that is in

216
00:12:48.070 --> 00:12:51.910
production of inflammatory cytokines, but also, as many of you probably

217
00:12:51.970 --> 00:12:55.420
know, the primary site for extragonadal production of

218
00:12:55.490 --> 00:12:57.990
estrogens is, in fact, adipose tissue.

219
00:12:58.310 --> 00:13:02.090
It's a pathological feature of adipose tissue that really

220
00:13:02.310 --> 00:13:06.270
nobody has any idea why it's produced there, and it's actually the

221
00:13:06.310 --> 00:13:09.570
primary reason that aromatase inhibitors are effective in

222
00:13:10.710 --> 00:13:14.510
the treatment of breast cancer patients, either in the prevention, the adjuvant, or

223
00:13:14.570 --> 00:13:18.270
the treatment setting, is because it's reducing the production of extragonadal

224
00:13:18.310 --> 00:13:18.760
estrogens.

225
00:13:19.870 --> 00:13:23.430
So why is a guy here who works on the estrogen receptor talking about

226
00:13:23.470 --> 00:13:23.970
cholesterol?

227
00:13:24.790 --> 00:13:28.250
And the reason is, as I said, both of these fields converged in my lab.

228
00:13:29.270 --> 00:13:32.670
As I said, I do want to introduce you to this because it'll help you understand the

229
00:13:32.750 --> 00:13:34.690
first part of the talk, and that is how

230
00:13:35.710 --> 00:13:39.630
cholesterol and dyslipidemia impacts ER-positive cancers.

231
00:13:40.510 --> 00:13:44.380
But what I think is even more surprising, and I think very surprising, is

232
00:13:44.410 --> 00:13:48.050
the impact and the mechanism by which hypercholesterolemia affects not

233
00:13:48.130 --> 00:13:51.810
only estrogen receptor-positive breast cancers, but cancers in

234
00:13:51.870 --> 00:13:52.210
general.

235
00:13:53.050 --> 00:13:56.810
So again, just to remind you for the first few slides, the estrogen receptor is a

236
00:13:56.870 --> 00:13:59.090
ligand-dependent transcription factors.

237
00:13:59.500 --> 00:14:00.470
Its role in the

238
00:14:01.990 --> 00:14:05.840
growth and progression of breast cancer is well established, and

239
00:14:05.950 --> 00:14:09.870
the majority of breast cancer, about 70%

240
00:14:09.910 --> 00:14:13.850
of them, whether they're in the early or late setting, at least the initial

241
00:14:13.870 --> 00:14:16.910
therapies are endocrine therapies which target the estrogen receptor.

242
00:14:18.410 --> 00:14:21.150
So this was of interest to me because... Let me back up.

243
00:14:21.210 --> 00:14:25.070
My group had not only developed drugs to inhibit the estrogen receptor, but we'd

244
00:14:25.130 --> 00:14:28.830
also developed this whole concept of functional allostery, and that

245
00:14:28.910 --> 00:14:32.790
is different ligands could bind to the receptor, drive the receptor into

246
00:14:32.810 --> 00:14:34.900
different shapes, and you get different biologies.

247
00:14:35.390 --> 00:14:39.360
And that led to the development of a series of molecules called SERMs, selective

248
00:14:39.490 --> 00:14:43.330
estrogen receptor modulators. Tamoxifen is not an antagonist,

249
00:14:43.430 --> 00:14:47.070
it's a SERM, because sometimes it functions as an agonist, sometimes it functions

250
00:14:47.110 --> 00:14:50.690
as an antagonist. And so it was that hat on, if you want.

251
00:14:50.750 --> 00:14:54.620
I had that hat on when I saw this paper by a very good colleague, a friend of mine,

252
00:14:54.710 --> 00:14:57.750
David Mangelsdorf, who unfortunately passed away last year.

253
00:14:58.230 --> 00:15:01.990
David was at UT Southwest, and he's very much interested in bile acid

254
00:15:02.030 --> 00:15:05.490
receptors. And so he had a side project in the lab

255
00:15:05.770 --> 00:15:06.430
looking at

256
00:15:07.950 --> 00:15:11.890
agents that would modulate bile acid receptors, and a control he had in

257
00:15:11.910 --> 00:15:13.570
the assay was the estrogen receptor.

258
00:15:14.060 --> 00:15:17.250
And to make a very long story short, he published a fantastic paper in "Nature

259
00:15:17.310 --> 00:15:21.290
Medicine" that basically showed that this molecule, which I had never heard

260
00:15:21.330 --> 00:15:24.670
of before, 27-hydroxycholesterol, had some

261
00:15:24.770 --> 00:15:28.610
characteristics that suggested that it might actually bind the estrogen

262
00:15:28.690 --> 00:15:30.750
receptor and manifest some of the

263
00:15:30.890 --> 00:15:34.010
pathobiology of this oxyesterol.

264
00:15:35.050 --> 00:15:38.030
Well, we got interested in this, a young graduate student of mine.

265
00:15:38.050 --> 00:15:40.690
This is going back now nearly 20 years ago.

266
00:15:40.870 --> 00:15:42.910
I promise you I'm going to show you more recent data.

267
00:15:43.730 --> 00:15:46.430
Which basically we asked the question, was David right?

268
00:15:46.750 --> 00:15:49.470
Was this, in fact, A, an estrogen receptor modulator?

269
00:15:49.970 --> 00:15:53.570
B, was it a SERM? And C, did it have any role

270
00:15:53.850 --> 00:15:55.450
in breast cancer pathobiology?

271
00:15:56.330 --> 00:15:59.850
So Carolyn, who, as I said, was a graduate student at the time, set up a very

272
00:15:59.970 --> 00:16:03.630
simple assay. It's a transcription assay to read out on estrogen

273
00:16:03.670 --> 00:16:07.590
receptor activity. And what you can see is here is that this is looking on the

274
00:16:07.690 --> 00:16:11.650
y-axis at the normalized response, and this is dose of the input drugs.

275
00:16:12.010 --> 00:16:14.430
This is estradiol activating transcription beautifully.

276
00:16:14.850 --> 00:16:18.650
This is 27-hydroxycholesterol shifted over by about

277
00:16:18.690 --> 00:16:19.690
three logs or so,

278
00:16:21.570 --> 00:16:24.590
functioning as a very weak, if you want, or less potent estrogen.

279
00:16:24.910 --> 00:16:28.730
But it's a classical partial agonist because if you take the 100%

280
00:16:28.810 --> 00:16:31.990
activation of the estrogen receptor and you add increasing concentration to

281
00:16:32.090 --> 00:16:35.690
27HC, you inhibit back down to its 100% level.

282
00:16:35.730 --> 00:16:38.790
Now, before everyone gets up and leaves the room and says, "Ah, God, this is so

283
00:16:38.850 --> 00:16:42.370
low," it turns out this is well within the circulating limits

284
00:16:42.470 --> 00:16:45.090
of 27-hydroxycholesterol. I'll show you that in a minute.

285
00:16:45.850 --> 00:16:49.750
And then again, this is on classical target genes, showing that it functions as

286
00:16:49.810 --> 00:16:51.750
estradiol or functions as a pure agonist.

287
00:16:52.250 --> 00:16:54.770
27-hydroxycholesterol is a partial agonist.

288
00:16:55.010 --> 00:16:57.490
And if you knock out the estrogen receptor, you lose all of those

289
00:16:57.550 --> 00:17:01.440
responses. So this was interesting to us because it said that

290
00:17:01.490 --> 00:17:05.131
possibly 27-hydroxycholesterol could be an

291
00:17:05.190 --> 00:17:08.210
endogenous SERM. Now, I'm just going to jump forward and tell you something, that

292
00:17:08.290 --> 00:17:12.171
after we published our first paper on this, I got a call from a guy called Michael

293
00:17:12.190 --> 00:17:15.381
Baker, who's a comparative evolutionary biologist at

294
00:17:15.411 --> 00:17:19.320
UCSD, and he said, "Well, you clearly don't read my papers because we have been

295
00:17:19.320 --> 00:17:22.570
talking about 27HC as a vestigial estrogen for

296
00:17:22.651 --> 00:17:25.040
years." And so I said, "Well, where did you publish that?" And he said, "Oh, it's

297
00:17:25.090 --> 00:17:29.050
in 'The Journal of Entomology.'" That's not one of the ones I read very often, so I

298
00:17:29.090 --> 00:17:33.030
apologize for missing that. But the bottom line was is that there was some evidence

299
00:17:33.070 --> 00:17:34.910
that this actually was a vestigial estrogen.

300
00:17:35.770 --> 00:17:37.450
So where it comes from, it's actually

301
00:17:38.470 --> 00:17:41.810
produced in a stoichiometric manner by the actions of this

302
00:17:41.850 --> 00:17:45.530
macrophage-expressed enzyme called CYP27A1

303
00:17:45.730 --> 00:17:49.470
into 27-hydroxycholesterol. And David Russell, in

304
00:17:49.510 --> 00:17:53.250
collaboration with Brown and Goldstein, figured out what this molecule did about 20

305
00:17:53.270 --> 00:17:56.190
years ago in the cholesterol biosynthesis pathway.

306
00:17:56.230 --> 00:17:59.570
It actually works as a feedback mechanism to inhibit HMG CoA

307
00:17:59.590 --> 00:18:02.910
reductase to basically tell the cell, you've made enough cholesterol.

308
00:18:02.950 --> 00:18:06.770
It's a negative feedback. It basically works as a direct inhibitor of HMG CoA

309
00:18:06.790 --> 00:18:10.470
reductase, but it also blocks the activation of the SREBPs.

310
00:18:11.630 --> 00:18:11.950
And so

311
00:18:13.370 --> 00:18:16.050
Eric Nelson, who's now a faculty member in

312
00:18:16.110 --> 00:18:18.374
IllinoisAt the University of Illinois.

313
00:18:18.734 --> 00:18:22.314
Basically, when he was a graduate or a postdoc in my lab, made a mouse where he

314
00:18:22.354 --> 00:18:25.514
knocked out CYP27A1, this regulatory

315
00:18:25.594 --> 00:18:28.524
enzyme. And when he went-- I beg your pardon. I'm going to go back. Sorry.

316
00:18:28.914 --> 00:18:30.794
I'm sorry. I'll tell you that in a second.

317
00:18:30.874 --> 00:18:34.114
I forgot where-- I changed the slides this morning. Sorry, I want to go back here.

318
00:18:34.134 --> 00:18:38.054
So 27HC. I want to nail down one other point first, and that is I

319
00:18:38.134 --> 00:18:41.114
made a statement that I need to provide some background to, and that is that

320
00:18:41.494 --> 00:18:45.154
27-hydroxycholesterol is stoichiometrically related,

321
00:18:45.454 --> 00:18:47.814
if you want, to HDL and LDL cholesterol.

322
00:18:48.324 --> 00:18:51.714
And so this study was done in collaboration with Signe Borquist in Aarhus

323
00:18:51.814 --> 00:18:54.574
University in Denmark and her graduate student,

324
00:18:55.774 --> 00:18:58.634
Sika Gimberg. And what they did was they worked with us.

325
00:18:58.694 --> 00:19:01.754
We developed a radioimmunoassay for

326
00:19:01.874 --> 00:19:05.794
27-hydroxycholesterol. And what we found was is that, with phenomenal

327
00:19:05.914 --> 00:19:09.654
R-squared values, that there was a great correlation between total cholesterol,

328
00:19:09.994 --> 00:19:12.214
LDL cholesterol, and 27HC.

329
00:19:13.534 --> 00:19:17.504
The classic test of whether this is important in cancer is to go and take

330
00:19:17.504 --> 00:19:21.264
a tumor xenograft model and ask, will this drug support the

331
00:19:21.314 --> 00:19:25.074
growth of a tumor? In our field, this is the gold standard

332
00:19:25.154 --> 00:19:27.734
test for something to be important or not.

333
00:19:28.274 --> 00:19:31.334
So this is just, I'm not going to go through this in very much detail because it's

334
00:19:31.694 --> 00:19:35.354
quite simple. This is a tumor that is growing, an estrogen receptor-positive tumor

335
00:19:35.394 --> 00:19:37.054
in a mouse growing with estradiol.

336
00:19:37.474 --> 00:19:41.354
If I come along and I add in 27-hydroxycholesterol, the tumor grows.

337
00:19:41.414 --> 00:19:42.254
If I continue it on

338
00:19:43.514 --> 00:19:46.114
27-hydroxycholesterol, the tumor continues to grow.

339
00:19:46.474 --> 00:19:50.374
If I block it with a pure antagonist of the estrogen receptor, I can attenuate

340
00:19:50.394 --> 00:19:54.174
this. If I withdraw the 27HC at this point, the tumors will

341
00:19:54.214 --> 00:19:57.844
regress. So by the criteria others and we have

342
00:19:57.854 --> 00:19:58.714
established as

343
00:20:00.654 --> 00:20:04.294
required to claim something to have functional estrogenic activity,

344
00:20:04.574 --> 00:20:08.454
this molecule does. And so back then to that experiment that I jumped to,

345
00:20:08.794 --> 00:20:12.234
and that was that Eric went and said, "Well, if that's true, I should be able to

346
00:20:12.254 --> 00:20:16.134
genetically manipulate the levels of 27HC, and rather

347
00:20:16.174 --> 00:20:19.814
than now using xenograft models, I'm going to use

348
00:20:19.914 --> 00:20:23.854
syngeneic models of breast cancer." And so as most people know, there

349
00:20:23.874 --> 00:20:27.073
are very few good models of ER-positive breast cancer.

350
00:20:27.513 --> 00:20:30.034
The MMTV-PyMT model is the best one.

351
00:20:30.874 --> 00:20:34.534
And you can see here is that when Eric knocked out this enzyme genetically, now

352
00:20:34.574 --> 00:20:38.494
this was a whole body knockout, I will tell you, we get exactly

353
00:20:38.534 --> 00:20:41.654
the same thing if we just do a macrophage-specific knockout.

354
00:20:41.694 --> 00:20:44.834
So that's the primary point of conversion of cholesterol to

355
00:20:44.954 --> 00:20:48.714
27HC. But you can see here that if you just look at absolute tumor

356
00:20:48.794 --> 00:20:52.274
volume, that the knockout alone of this particular enzyme

357
00:20:52.554 --> 00:20:54.114
decreases the growth of these tumors.

358
00:20:54.734 --> 00:20:58.634
If you look at tumor latency, because this is a genetic model, you

359
00:20:58.674 --> 00:21:02.434
can see that tumor latency in the knockout mouse is dramatically delayed,

360
00:21:02.874 --> 00:21:05.994
and survival is dramatically improved in these mice.

361
00:21:06.774 --> 00:21:08.684
Now, I'm not going to tell you right now, but it turns out that

362
00:21:08.714 --> 00:21:12.234
27-hydroxycholesterol is metabolized by another enzyme called

363
00:21:12.254 --> 00:21:15.894
CYP7B1. And what we did was when we knocked out that

364
00:21:16.474 --> 00:21:19.854
enzyme, 27HC builds up in the animals, and you get

365
00:21:19.914 --> 00:21:22.464
exactly the same, the expected response.

366
00:21:22.774 --> 00:21:25.404
Tumors appear faster and grow faster.

367
00:21:26.264 --> 00:21:29.124
And so what this basically then suggested to us was is that

368
00:21:29.254 --> 00:21:33.154
27HC, which was, as I said, Brown and Goldstein and David

369
00:21:33.214 --> 00:21:36.954
Russell had figured out to be a negative regulator of HMG

370
00:21:37.034 --> 00:21:40.754
CoA reductase and to basically be a part of a negative feedback

371
00:21:40.814 --> 00:21:44.694
loop that limits production of cholesterol, is in fact an

372
00:21:44.734 --> 00:21:48.574
estrogen receptor modulator. In our early writings then, what we

373
00:21:48.614 --> 00:21:52.154
said was, this was a paradox, because if you have something that's going to

374
00:21:52.194 --> 00:21:56.094
inhibit a molecule that's required for cancer cell biology, how is

375
00:21:56.174 --> 00:21:58.314
it then that it actually promotes the growth of tumors?

376
00:21:58.874 --> 00:22:00.534
And we had a hand-waving answer

377
00:22:01.574 --> 00:22:05.334
that I think we know a bit much more and we have better support for right now,

378
00:22:05.694 --> 00:22:09.614
is that the effects of the estrogen override the effects of

379
00:22:09.654 --> 00:22:12.834
the negative feedback. And I'll tell you why that happens in a few

380
00:22:12.874 --> 00:22:16.774
minutes. So the bottom line is that we were about to finish the

381
00:22:16.794 --> 00:22:20.574
study and walk away. We had proven that 27-hydroxycholesterol was

382
00:22:20.594 --> 00:22:23.534
related with respect to levels of cholesterol.

383
00:22:23.914 --> 00:22:26.054
We'd shown that it was an estrogen receptor modulator.

384
00:22:26.454 --> 00:22:30.094
We'd been able to publish several papers on various mechanisms of this, and we're

385
00:22:30.134 --> 00:22:30.874
ready to move on.

386
00:22:31.954 --> 00:22:34.273
And basically just say, "Mission accomplished.

387
00:22:34.374 --> 00:22:37.974
We've made a link between hypercholesterolemia and ER-positive breast

388
00:22:38.014 --> 00:22:38.473
cancers."

389
00:22:39.734 --> 00:22:42.634
However, I had a postdoc in the lab, Wen Liu.

390
00:22:43.494 --> 00:22:46.854
And Wen was very much interested in literature, which also said that

391
00:22:46.894 --> 00:22:50.874
dyslipidemia was associated with increased risk of triple-negative

392
00:22:50.884 --> 00:22:54.764
breast cancer. And we basically had no explanation as to

393
00:22:54.794 --> 00:22:58.783
why this could be, because everything we had done was focused on

394
00:22:58.814 --> 00:23:02.774
the estrogen receptor. And so she made these models, which to

395
00:23:02.794 --> 00:23:05.494
be honest with you, she did them on the side because I probably would never have

396
00:23:05.554 --> 00:23:08.714
supported this project. It took too long and just seemed like a bit of a

397
00:23:08.774 --> 00:23:12.334
hair-brained idea to me. But what she did was, she

398
00:23:12.374 --> 00:23:16.234
realized that 27HC, as I told you, is a negative regulator of cholesterol

399
00:23:16.294 --> 00:23:19.694
biosynthesis, and everything that we had ever done in the lab shown that in

400
00:23:19.714 --> 00:23:22.814
estrogen receptor-negative cells, it inhibited the growth of those cells.

401
00:23:23.214 --> 00:23:27.134
Exactly as you'd expect it. You shut down cholesterol biosynthesis, cells don't

402
00:23:27.174 --> 00:23:29.334
like it, and they don't progress.

403
00:23:30.474 --> 00:23:34.214
But what actually Wen found was is that if you basically let them sit

404
00:23:34.224 --> 00:23:37.634
there for about a month, you let these cells sit in the presence of

405
00:23:37.734 --> 00:23:40.634
27HC, what happens is subclones grow out,

406
00:23:41.494 --> 00:23:45.294
and the subclones are unbelievably resistant to the

407
00:23:45.304 --> 00:23:49.154
effects of 27HC. So for instance, here is a model of melanoma,

408
00:23:49.234 --> 00:23:53.174
for instance, and you can see that 27HC really does not inhibit the growth of

409
00:23:53.214 --> 00:23:56.234
these melanoma cells. These are two different breast cancer models.

410
00:23:56.294 --> 00:24:00.034
You see 27HC inhibiting these, and you look again in the resistant cells, nothing

411
00:24:00.044 --> 00:24:03.434
happens. Well, that was okay, but I just told you

412
00:24:03.574 --> 00:24:05.974
27HC is part of a negative feedback loop.

413
00:24:06.254 --> 00:24:08.654
And so we said, "Well, Wen, that's not a surprise.

414
00:24:08.894 --> 00:24:12.654
You've just found a mutation in the negative feedback." It turns out she didn't.

415
00:24:12.934 --> 00:24:16.534
It turns out that the negative feedback loop, shown here by gene expression

416
00:24:16.574 --> 00:24:19.254
analysis, was intact. This is the sensitive cells.

417
00:24:19.474 --> 00:24:23.294
These are all the enzymes that should have been inhibited by 27HC, and they

418
00:24:23.394 --> 00:24:27.274
are. Here's in the resistant cells, and they're still inhibited in both models.

419
00:24:27.994 --> 00:24:31.326
So there was something else going on.But what really got my

420
00:24:31.366 --> 00:24:33.906
attention was the next model, the next experiment.

421
00:24:34.346 --> 00:24:38.266
This, to me, is probably one of the most dramatic results, bar none, I've

422
00:24:38.306 --> 00:24:41.006
ever seen in my lab. These are tumors.

423
00:24:41.226 --> 00:24:44.986
These are all isogenic lines. And all I've

424
00:24:45.026 --> 00:24:48.086
done is selected out for subclones within a

425
00:24:48.126 --> 00:24:51.986
population of breast cancer cells, the PY230 model,

426
00:24:52.326 --> 00:24:56.276
4T1 model, and then this is another breast cancer model, and

427
00:24:56.326 --> 00:24:59.946
this is a melanoma model. Look at this. These are animal studies.

428
00:25:00.186 --> 00:25:03.946
These cells, if you inject them into mice, it takes forever for them to

429
00:25:03.986 --> 00:25:07.526
grow. Look how tumorigenic they were. Look at these ones, 4T1.

430
00:25:07.706 --> 00:25:10.046
These are incredibly tumorigenic.

431
00:25:10.566 --> 00:25:14.026
Now remember, all I have done is grown-- Actually, I said that wrong.

432
00:25:14.226 --> 00:25:17.446
All Wen did was grow these cells in the presence of

433
00:25:17.646 --> 00:25:20.906
27-hydroxycholesterol, and she's now made these cells

434
00:25:21.186 --> 00:25:25.096
unbelievably tumorigenic. And I hope you're impressed

435
00:25:25.126 --> 00:25:28.486
by this slide because before I finish, I'm going to show you another slide, which

436
00:25:28.566 --> 00:25:32.486
I'm going to say is even more dramatic and more important than this.

437
00:25:33.586 --> 00:25:33.726
So

438
00:25:35.026 --> 00:25:38.946
what Wen wanted to do then was ask the question, if these cells are

439
00:25:39.026 --> 00:25:40.026
more tumorigenic,

440
00:25:40.946 --> 00:25:44.586
are they more metastatic? Now, for us in the cancer field, as you know, that's more

441
00:25:44.606 --> 00:25:48.546
important to look at because the best cure for a primary tumor is a surgeon's

442
00:25:48.566 --> 00:25:50.666
knife, and it's metastases that get you.

443
00:25:51.176 --> 00:25:54.446
And it turns out that these cells are incredibly tumorigenic.

444
00:25:55.006 --> 00:25:55.966
It's funny, these

445
00:25:57.026 --> 00:26:00.746
cancer cells are labeled with luciferase, and you can see in the sensitive

446
00:26:00.806 --> 00:26:04.706
lines when you inject them in the tail vein, none of these form metastatic

447
00:26:04.766 --> 00:26:08.326
lesions. But if you inject the isogenic resistant

448
00:26:08.346 --> 00:26:10.566
versions, they all form metastatic lesions.

449
00:26:11.086 --> 00:26:14.826
The luciferase assay just doesn't do this justice because actually all you need to

450
00:26:14.846 --> 00:26:16.566
do is look at the lungs from these animals.

451
00:26:16.866 --> 00:26:20.746
You can see here lovely pink lungs with very few little nodules, and these things

452
00:26:20.756 --> 00:26:23.646
look like walnuts. Just incredible.

453
00:26:23.666 --> 00:26:25.686
And I'm going to say, this is not just one line.

454
00:26:25.726 --> 00:26:29.206
This was every line we ever looked at.

455
00:26:29.226 --> 00:26:31.766
And so the question then became was, how is this happening?

456
00:26:32.316 --> 00:26:35.986
And so it was interesting because remember I just told you that

457
00:26:36.126 --> 00:26:39.626
27-HC inhibits the production of

458
00:26:39.646 --> 00:26:40.305
cholesterol.

459
00:26:41.186 --> 00:26:45.026
It also blocks the activation of SREBP 1 and 2.

460
00:26:45.406 --> 00:26:48.446
And so the question was, how could these cells possibly survive?

461
00:26:48.906 --> 00:26:52.426
It turns out what they're doing is they are dramatically taking up lipids.

462
00:26:52.926 --> 00:26:56.226
Okay? And you can see that these are the sensitive and the resistant versions of

463
00:26:56.286 --> 00:26:59.426
all of these lines, and this is the quantitation out here.

464
00:26:59.446 --> 00:27:02.526
They're basically non-selectively taking up lipids.

465
00:27:02.776 --> 00:27:05.766
Turns out that, of course, they're taking up cholesterol, but they're taking up

466
00:27:05.826 --> 00:27:09.506
mono and polyunsaturated acids. They're just sucking up anything they can get.

467
00:27:09.546 --> 00:27:10.746
They're stressed out of their minds.

468
00:27:11.576 --> 00:27:14.716
And so the reason that that was disappointing was because we couldn't

469
00:27:14.746 --> 00:27:18.396
narrow it down to one specific transporter that was

470
00:27:18.426 --> 00:27:20.256
upregulated. But that was one thing.

471
00:27:20.706 --> 00:27:23.936
But the second thing is, when you have a bright postdoc, they see something like

472
00:27:23.986 --> 00:27:26.686
this, and they come up with an explanation as to why it could be linked to the

473
00:27:26.706 --> 00:27:30.266
biology. I never heard of a process called ferroptosis.

474
00:27:30.366 --> 00:27:31.966
Never heard of it until we started doing this.

475
00:27:32.535 --> 00:27:36.326
And it turns out, as most of you know, that if you take palmitate, the

476
00:27:36.366 --> 00:27:39.426
fatty acid, and you put it on the cells, they die, and they die because of

477
00:27:39.436 --> 00:27:43.226
ferroptosis. Okay? It's a process that occurs

478
00:27:43.306 --> 00:27:45.646
because the lipids are taken into the cell.

479
00:27:45.686 --> 00:27:49.566
They form these lipid oxides, which are incorporated into membranes, which

480
00:27:49.606 --> 00:27:52.986
basically kills the cells. So why do cells survive that?

481
00:27:53.206 --> 00:27:56.966
Well, it turns out there's a molecule called GPX4 that's in the

482
00:27:57.006 --> 00:28:00.266
cell that is actually a gatekeeper, one of the gatekeepers for

483
00:28:00.326 --> 00:28:01.086
ferroptosis.

