730
00:41:49.270 --> 00:41:50.150
of malignancies.

731
00:41:50.970 --> 00:41:54.670
This paper was provocative but was quite limited, due to an inability to

732
00:41:54.730 --> 00:41:57.600
control for co-founders, including smoking.

733
00:41:58.290 --> 00:42:01.780
But since then, other groups have really expanded on this, including a beautiful

734
00:42:01.830 --> 00:42:04.990
study from Japan showing that people with different forms of

735
00:42:05.050 --> 00:42:08.130
cardiovascular disease are at higher risk of cancer.

736
00:42:08.890 --> 00:42:12.150
And then a report from Canada showing the opposite to be true, and that various

737
00:42:12.230 --> 00:42:15.710
forms of malignancy put you at higher risk of heart disease.

738
00:42:16.970 --> 00:42:20.090
Now, these papers were a big advance, but they had their own limitations.

739
00:42:20.590 --> 00:42:24.450
And so, our group set out to try to use large claim

740
00:42:24.460 --> 00:42:26.890
data sets to expand these findings.

741
00:42:26.920 --> 00:42:30.710
And leveraging data for more than 30 million individuals, we

742
00:42:30.810 --> 00:42:33.100
found this interesting observation that

743
00:42:33.890 --> 00:42:37.380
non-atherosclerotic forms of disease, like valve disease or

744
00:42:37.450 --> 00:42:40.370
arrhythmia, do not appear to put you at higher risk of

745
00:42:40.430 --> 00:42:43.958
cancer.But there's a rather specific association with

746
00:42:44.058 --> 00:42:47.898
atherosclerotic forms. And because of our power, we were

747
00:42:47.938 --> 00:42:51.518
able to resolve these relationships with a wide range of

748
00:42:51.598 --> 00:42:52.958
individual malignancies.

749
00:42:54.018 --> 00:42:57.418
And because we had access to a large number of different datasets with

750
00:42:57.798 --> 00:43:01.578
more and less information about comorbidities, we were able to find that

751
00:43:01.638 --> 00:43:05.358
these patterns would persist even when we did the best we could to

752
00:43:05.398 --> 00:43:08.858
adjust for other confounding factors like obesity,

753
00:43:10.038 --> 00:43:11.658
diabetes, smoking, et cetera.

754
00:43:13.298 --> 00:43:16.438
Now, we've got some ongoing work in the lab, some of it's published, some of it's

755
00:43:16.498 --> 00:43:20.058
coming out soon, showing that this will extend to other types of

756
00:43:20.078 --> 00:43:23.218
cardiovascular disease. I'm a vascular medicine doctor.

757
00:43:23.478 --> 00:43:27.218
I take care of PAD. We've seen the same association with this

758
00:43:27.258 --> 00:43:31.218
disease. We've found that patients with aortic aneurysms are

759
00:43:31.298 --> 00:43:33.538
also at higher risk of developing malignancy.

760
00:43:34.678 --> 00:43:38.518
And there seems to be a gene dosage type effect in people that have

761
00:43:38.578 --> 00:43:42.558
atherosclerosis affecting multiple vascular beds, seem to

762
00:43:42.618 --> 00:43:45.318
have a stepwise increase in this relationship with

763
00:43:45.378 --> 00:43:49.198
cancer. And I think that to Donald's point,

764
00:43:49.468 --> 00:43:53.318
this does have potentially clinical relevance, and

765
00:43:53.378 --> 00:43:57.138
we've begun to identify associations not with the presence of cancer,

766
00:43:57.618 --> 00:44:01.578
but also metastatic cancer. And so there may come a time in the

767
00:44:01.618 --> 00:44:05.048
future where getting diagnosed with heart disease may be a

768
00:44:05.078 --> 00:44:08.338
threshold where you might offer screening for

769
00:44:08.378 --> 00:44:11.958
mammography or colonoscopy at a younger age so that you can

770
00:44:12.018 --> 00:44:15.398
avoid having these late diagnoses which will present with

771
00:44:15.678 --> 00:44:16.458
metastasis.

772
00:44:18.408 --> 00:44:22.398
And then finally, Donald already started to allude to this about lipid lowering.

773
00:44:23.118 --> 00:44:27.058
But there is a concept that addressing all of the known cardiovascular risk factors

774
00:44:27.098 --> 00:44:30.278
may have benefit. This has been shown by several groups, and we

775
00:44:30.938 --> 00:44:32.798
recently published a meta-analysis.

776
00:44:33.338 --> 00:44:37.238
And this would suggest that if you can take care of the

777
00:44:37.318 --> 00:44:41.258
Life's Essential Eights, which are the risk factors that the American

778
00:44:41.338 --> 00:44:45.318
Heart Association tells us to work on for heart disease, that you

779
00:44:45.378 --> 00:44:49.138
may enjoy as much as a 50% reduction in developing

780
00:44:49.238 --> 00:44:50.338
cancer down the road.

781
00:44:51.258 --> 00:44:54.518
So at least food for thought about public health initiatives.

782
00:44:56.338 --> 00:44:59.858
But what I wanted to talk about today is if this field should move

783
00:44:59.938 --> 00:45:03.808
beyond shared risk factors and start to focus on this

784
00:45:03.858 --> 00:45:07.278
concept of overlapping biological mechanisms.

785
00:45:07.958 --> 00:45:11.798
And this is a topic that our lab has been thinking about, amongst

786
00:45:11.818 --> 00:45:14.358
many others now, for more than a decade.

787
00:45:14.878 --> 00:45:18.618
And I won't have time to go through all of the considerations that we've started to

788
00:45:18.698 --> 00:45:22.538
notice. But I wanted to point out a few because I think they're pretty provocative.

789
00:45:24.138 --> 00:45:27.398
Our lab is really heavy on using unbiased human genetics, and

790
00:45:27.938 --> 00:45:31.338
anybody that's followed these GWAS stories over the year will

791
00:45:31.398 --> 00:45:35.098
know that to this day, the head and shoulders most

792
00:45:35.138 --> 00:45:39.098
important thing that you can inherit from your parents that will put you at risk

793
00:45:39.118 --> 00:45:42.418
for having a myocardial infarction are the variants at chromosome

794
00:45:42.578 --> 00:45:46.438
9p21. And this just floored me when these papers

795
00:45:46.478 --> 00:45:49.798
were published because these loci are not in lipid

796
00:45:49.838 --> 00:45:53.558
metabolism or blood pressure or smoking or diabetes

797
00:45:54.238 --> 00:45:57.878
loci. This is actually in the well-known tumor suppressor

798
00:45:57.958 --> 00:46:01.938
locus for p15 or CDKN2B, suggesting that the most

799
00:46:01.978 --> 00:46:05.938
important thing that puts you at higher genetic risk for heart disease has

800
00:46:05.958 --> 00:46:09.838
nothing to do with our traditional risk factors, but instead may relate

801
00:46:09.898 --> 00:46:12.778
to cell cycle regulation.

802
00:46:13.658 --> 00:46:17.338
Javed told us about clonal hematopoiesis, which is one of the more fascinating

803
00:46:17.358 --> 00:46:21.298
discoveries of the last decade from Sid Jaiswal and Ben Ebert and others,

804
00:46:22.158 --> 00:46:25.818
which, as Javed mentioned, is a well-known pattern where these

805
00:46:25.838 --> 00:46:29.558
somatic mutations will put you at higher risk for hematological malignancies.

806
00:46:30.098 --> 00:46:34.068
But there's an even greater impact on your risk of atherosclerotic disease,

807
00:46:34.598 --> 00:46:38.498
which Javed mentioned is on the order of diabetes and I think may be as high

808
00:46:38.538 --> 00:46:42.147
as smoking, suggesting that, wow, what an important

809
00:46:42.518 --> 00:46:46.398
risk factor that we weren't aware of that yet again hearkens back to

810
00:46:46.778 --> 00:46:50.498
biology that's probably classically more associated with the field of

811
00:46:50.538 --> 00:46:52.218
oncology than cardiology.

812
00:46:54.198 --> 00:46:57.878
Our lab has also thought a lot about this concept of the cancer stem

813
00:46:57.978 --> 00:47:01.918
cell and this idea that this may be the mechanism by which you can have

814
00:47:02.238 --> 00:47:06.218
an initial tumor induction and remission, and then

815
00:47:06.278 --> 00:47:10.128
the cancer will recur years or decades later and often is

816
00:47:10.158 --> 00:47:11.138
widely metastatic.

817
00:47:11.998 --> 00:47:15.878
We and others have begun to use multicolor lineage tracers, and at

818
00:47:15.938 --> 00:47:19.098
least in mouse models, we see that diseases like

819
00:47:19.178 --> 00:47:23.058
atherosclerosis clearly have a clonal component

820
00:47:23.578 --> 00:47:27.018
that is very reminiscent of the cancer stem cell hypothesis.

821
00:47:27.518 --> 00:47:31.278
So again, this idea that there may be such a thing as an

822
00:47:31.298 --> 00:47:35.118
atherosclerotic stem cell that will behave in a very similar fashion.

823
00:47:36.218 --> 00:47:40.058
And then one of the main areas that our lab works on is this concept

824
00:47:40.418 --> 00:47:43.998
of failed efferocytosis. And this is really a

825
00:47:44.058 --> 00:47:47.838
concept that we borrowed from the oncology field, where tumor

826
00:47:47.938 --> 00:47:51.558
cells will upregulate what are known as don't eat me molecules

827
00:47:51.958 --> 00:47:54.878
that will help them escape the tumoricidal macrophage.

828
00:47:55.818 --> 00:47:59.758
And then our lab has shown that the exact same pathways are turned on in

829
00:47:59.778 --> 00:48:03.618
atherosclerosis, and we have begun to hypothesize that this

830
00:48:03.678 --> 00:48:05.638
may be what allows these cells to

831
00:48:06.698 --> 00:48:10.338
escape the immune surveillance, not be removed by

832
00:48:10.678 --> 00:48:14.238
the macrophages in the plaque, and then that this will allow the plaque to

833
00:48:14.278 --> 00:48:18.168
expand, causing coronary disease, very similar to why

834
00:48:18.218 --> 00:48:19.718
the cancer is allowed to grow.

835
00:48:21.918 --> 00:48:25.238
And then, I think to Donald's point, you can't just complain about it.

836
00:48:25.318 --> 00:48:26.798
You have to have a solution for it.

837
00:48:27.638 --> 00:48:31.418
We have taken advantage of this overlapping link between cancer and heart

838
00:48:31.498 --> 00:48:34.578
disease to pursue integrated genomics.

839
00:48:34.608 --> 00:48:38.478
And when we blend the datasets, we can start to identify patterns that may

840
00:48:38.518 --> 00:48:42.378
be mutually detrimental. And then we can filter these through

841
00:48:42.438 --> 00:48:46.358
drug repurposing algorithms to try to find medicines that may one day be able to

842
00:48:46.398 --> 00:48:49.798
help both diseases very similar to what we just heard about with

843
00:48:49.818 --> 00:48:53.568
statins.But

844
00:48:53.848 --> 00:48:56.848
for today, what I really want to do is move from just these

845
00:48:56.948 --> 00:49:00.928
associations to actual causation and

846
00:49:00.988 --> 00:49:04.968
start to ask the question of whether having one disease may

847
00:49:05.028 --> 00:49:08.868
induce some systemic changes that can then circulate throughout the

848
00:49:08.888 --> 00:49:12.828
body to lead to an increase in the other disease or vice versa.

849
00:49:14.768 --> 00:49:18.428
And I think if any of you are curious about whether having heart disease can

850
00:49:18.468 --> 00:49:19.348
produce cancer,

851
00:49:20.148 --> 00:49:24.068
you're in for a treat today because our next speaker is one of the world's

852
00:49:24.128 --> 00:49:27.978
experts on this concept. And so stay tuned for a great story

853
00:49:28.008 --> 00:49:30.868
about this that I'm looking forward to hearing.

854
00:49:31.228 --> 00:49:34.288
But for my part today, I want to share some unpublished work

855
00:49:34.928 --> 00:49:38.848
from a really talented person sitting here in the room, Lingfeng Luo,

856
00:49:38.908 --> 00:49:42.168
who is one of the junior faculty colleagues at Stanford.

857
00:49:42.788 --> 00:49:46.768
And he has been working on this really fantastic project trying

858
00:49:46.808 --> 00:49:49.848
to understand if cancer may directly accelerate

859
00:49:49.888 --> 00:49:53.588
atherosclerosis. And I'll point out that he's going to give a more full description

860
00:49:53.628 --> 00:49:55.188
of this work on Tuesday morning.

861
00:49:57.168 --> 00:50:00.888
So Lingfeng set out to ask a very simple question about whether implanting

862
00:50:01.008 --> 00:50:04.148
tumors in mice can directly accelerate

863
00:50:04.158 --> 00:50:07.738
atherosclerosis. And when he did this, he found that yes,

864
00:50:08.608 --> 00:50:12.538
if you implant colon cancers into the flank of a mouse, you will have

865
00:50:12.628 --> 00:50:14.868
a modest increase in that plaque size.

866
00:50:15.628 --> 00:50:19.608
But for those that look at these types of experiments, you'll note that this is not

867
00:50:20.208 --> 00:50:23.348
a dramatic increase in the overall size of the plaque.

868
00:50:25.328 --> 00:50:28.588
What was different, though, was the characteristics of the plaque.

869
00:50:28.688 --> 00:50:32.348
And in contrast to the control mice, which have very

870
00:50:32.428 --> 00:50:35.848
little neovessels growing into the lesion and very little

871
00:50:35.888 --> 00:50:39.588
intraplaque hemorrhage, Lingfeng noted that the

872
00:50:39.628 --> 00:50:43.208
mice that were bearing tumors had plaques that were really

873
00:50:43.368 --> 00:50:46.048
riddled with these new neovessels that were growing in.

874
00:50:46.628 --> 00:50:50.468
And what he found was that these appeared to be fragile and were prone to rupture,

875
00:50:50.868 --> 00:50:52.988
which you can see here with this red cell stain.

876
00:50:53.628 --> 00:50:57.358
And regardless of the way that he quantified this, he saw that there was this

877
00:50:57.388 --> 00:50:58.958
plaque vulnerability phenotype.

878
00:50:59.427 --> 00:51:03.128
And from the cardiologist perspective, we think this matters because these

879
00:51:03.148 --> 00:51:06.828
plaque hemorrhages can destabilize the plaque and then

880
00:51:06.888 --> 00:51:10.497
ultimately lead to the plaque rupture that will lead to heart attack or stroke,

881
00:51:11.228 --> 00:51:13.758
thereby talking about its clinical significance.

882
00:51:15.908 --> 00:51:19.217
Lingfeng wanted to understand the mechanism by which cancer was promoting

883
00:51:19.268 --> 00:51:22.678
atherosclerosis. And so to do this, I'm going to briefly

884
00:51:22.768 --> 00:51:24.588
summarize a couple of years' worth of work.

885
00:51:25.368 --> 00:51:29.208
But Lingfeng implanted a wide range of tumors into mouse

886
00:51:29.308 --> 00:51:33.268
models and then harvested their vasculature for RNA sequencing.

887
00:51:34.508 --> 00:51:38.428
What he found was that the common pathways that were turned on were all, again,

888
00:51:38.528 --> 00:51:42.188
related to angiogenesis, which was reassuring based on the phenotypic

889
00:51:42.268 --> 00:51:43.308
findings we had found.

890
00:51:44.228 --> 00:51:47.968
And then when he looked across all of these diverse gene profiles that were

891
00:51:48.028 --> 00:51:50.228
turned on in a cancer-specific manner,

892
00:51:51.068 --> 00:51:54.728
he could then make a Venn diagram and see which were the common and preserved

893
00:51:54.828 --> 00:51:58.368
factors. And it turns out that only a single gene is

894
00:51:58.808 --> 00:52:02.688
uniquely and consistently dysregulated in the presence of cancer.

895
00:52:03.208 --> 00:52:06.848
And this is an angiogenic cytokine known as LRG1.

896
00:52:07.988 --> 00:52:11.188
Now, I won't have time to show you the data, but he has now gone on to look

897
00:52:11.288 --> 00:52:14.948
upstream of this, and using a variety of

898
00:52:14.968 --> 00:52:18.878
informatics approaches and proteomics approaches, he's found that

899
00:52:18.928 --> 00:52:22.908
this is likely due to increases in TNF secretion by the

900
00:52:22.948 --> 00:52:26.868
tumor. The TNF leads to this angiogenic cytokine, and

901
00:52:26.888 --> 00:52:29.648
he believes that this is leading to the increase in

902
00:52:29.668 --> 00:52:33.128
neovascularization that he's been observing in vivo.

903
00:52:35.708 --> 00:52:39.528
We wanted to know if this was a mouse-only phenomenon or if this is also occurring

904
00:52:39.568 --> 00:52:42.928
in humans. And so we partnered with our colleagues in Europe,

905
00:52:43.128 --> 00:52:46.488
and looking at cohorts of patients with and without cancer,

906
00:52:47.228 --> 00:52:50.228
we've made several observations that validate the mouse findings.

907
00:52:51.128 --> 00:52:54.777
We've seen that in the UK Biobank, cancer patients have higher levels of

908
00:52:54.828 --> 00:52:56.928
circulating TNF, as you might expect.

909
00:52:57.928 --> 00:53:01.848
Looking in plaque biobanks, we've seen that these people also have higher

910
00:53:01.888 --> 00:53:05.208
levels of this angiogenic factor in the plaque itself.

911
00:53:06.088 --> 00:53:09.637
And you can see this on histology, where LRG is upregulated

912
00:53:10.187 --> 00:53:14.137
if you look at endarterectomy samples taken from patients with cancer versus those

913
00:53:14.168 --> 00:53:17.448
without. And when they do machine learning to look at the

914
00:53:17.488 --> 00:53:21.448
factors that are most strongly associated with the presence of

915
00:53:21.488 --> 00:53:25.008
intraplaque hemorrhage within the plaque, they find that a history of

916
00:53:25.108 --> 00:53:28.868
cancer is one of the strongest predictors following only age,

917
00:53:29.368 --> 00:53:31.548
smoking status, and diabetes.

918
00:53:34.428 --> 00:53:38.008
So having mapped this mechanism, Lingfeng now believes that having

919
00:53:38.068 --> 00:53:41.908
cancer will increase your circulating TNF, which will drive this

920
00:53:41.988 --> 00:53:45.908
angiogenic cytokine in the blood vessel, which will destabilize

921
00:53:45.948 --> 00:53:47.628
the plaque leading to clinical events.

922
00:53:49.388 --> 00:53:52.918
He then wanted to know if we could intervene on this for therapeutic purposes.

923
00:53:53.758 --> 00:53:57.468
So to test this, we were fortunate to be able to use commercially

924
00:53:57.508 --> 00:54:01.448
available TNF inhibitors like etanercept, which are commonly used for

925
00:54:01.508 --> 00:54:02.078
autoimmune

926
00:54:02.948 --> 00:54:04.368
and rheumatological conditions.

927
00:54:04.948 --> 00:54:08.678
And when he does this, he finds that the plaques are not only smaller, but

928
00:54:08.788 --> 00:54:11.578
all of this intraplaque angiogenesis will go away.

929
00:54:12.948 --> 00:54:16.608
Now, you may also be aware that these TNF blockers have a black

930
00:54:16.688 --> 00:54:20.608
box warning because of their ability to induce fluid retention.

931
00:54:20.668 --> 00:54:24.548
So patients with congestive heart failure are not allowed to use these

932
00:54:24.608 --> 00:54:27.888
medicines. So this will limit our translational

933
00:54:28.488 --> 00:54:31.418
use for people that are trying to avoid cardiovascular disease.

934
00:54:32.288 --> 00:54:35.828
But he's also been able to go on and look downstream and using an

935
00:54:35.868 --> 00:54:39.798
shRNA to target the specific cytokine.

936
00:54:39.828 --> 00:54:42.978
He's seeing the same type of benefit where

937
00:54:43.828 --> 00:54:47.728
the angiogenesis is suppressed, and we are now working to make a blocking

938
00:54:47.808 --> 00:54:49.238
antibody against this

939
00:54:49.448 --> 00:54:53.320
target.But as we think about the

940
00:54:53.360 --> 00:54:57.259
likelihood that this should be translated to humans, the question is if

941
00:54:57.340 --> 00:55:00.940
this defect is fixed or if it may be something that we could go

942
00:55:01.080 --> 00:55:03.180
after for translational purposes.

943
00:55:04.700 --> 00:55:08.620
Now, this is where, as Javed pointed out, I was really lucky to get to work

944
00:55:08.660 --> 00:55:11.360
with one of the most talented postdocs I've come across.

945
00:55:11.450 --> 00:55:12.680
I don't know if you feel the same way, Javed.

946
00:55:12.960 --> 00:55:15.020
It's nice to have trainees that are smarter than us.

947
00:55:15.960 --> 00:55:19.940
And Ricky, who was a fellow in the lab and went off to train at MGH before he came

948
00:55:19.980 --> 00:55:23.720
back to UCSF, had this really great idea

949
00:55:23.800 --> 00:55:27.509
to try to address the confounding that is so common in

950
00:55:27.540 --> 00:55:31.380
epidemiological studies, and instead to look at cancers that can be

951
00:55:31.440 --> 00:55:34.980
cured with resection alone, where you're not having confounding from

952
00:55:35.040 --> 00:55:38.480
radiation or chemotherapy. And so he took, for example,

953
00:55:38.620 --> 00:55:41.740
prostate cancer, which often is treated with

954
00:55:42.220 --> 00:55:46.060
resection alone, and he will then say, "I wonder

955
00:55:46.100 --> 00:55:50.060
what's going to happen to the rate of revascularization in the years

956
00:55:50.080 --> 00:55:52.920
before and after the tumor is taken out."

957
00:55:53.980 --> 00:55:57.510
He could look at the rates of MI, PCI, and

958
00:55:57.600 --> 00:56:01.020
CABG in the three years leading up to surgery, have a blanking

959
00:56:01.160 --> 00:56:04.200
period around the time of the surgery to avoid

960
00:56:04.860 --> 00:56:08.820
postoperative complications, and then look at the rates years

961
00:56:08.960 --> 00:56:12.720
after the surgery. Now, prostate cancer is not

962
00:56:12.820 --> 00:56:16.420
one of the cancers that we had found was supposed to

963
00:56:16.500 --> 00:56:20.270
enhance atherosclerosis. So it was no surprise that

964
00:56:20.300 --> 00:56:24.220
once the tumors were taken out, that the rates of revascularization

965
00:56:24.260 --> 00:56:27.660
continued to climb. This makes sense because the patients are getting older.

966
00:56:28.380 --> 00:56:30.520
And so it didn't matter that their cancers came out.

967
